title: Future 4 Fins
description: This project uses spatial prioritation for recommendations of marine protected areas in the Mozambique Channel to protect 26 crtically endangered shark and ray species.
contents:
Scalloped hammerhead shark (Sphyrna lewini), Source: Galapagos National ParkThis project was my master’s thesis along with four other team members. The goal of our project was to help the government ensure the long-term persistence of sharks and rays in Mozambique through an expanded network of marine protected areas. We created a reproducible model in R that prioritized areas to protect 26 species of sharks and rays with the least cost to stakeholders. Our project ran scenarios that looked at different fishing pressures on these species and how the reserve design changed based on each stakeholder.
Learn more at https://www.future4fins.com/

title: Binary Logistic Regression
description: A study of two Palmetto bunch grass species using binary logistic regression analysis.
contents:
Show code

library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(GGally)
library(broom)
library(jtools)
library(dplyr)
library(kableExtra)



Task 2 - Palmetto binary logistic regression
Here, we’ll be using binary logistic regression to test feasibility of whether a palmetto is species Serenoa repens or Sabal etonia using variables plant height (height), canopy length (length), canopy width (width), and number of green leaves (green_lvs). The data is collected over 5-year intervals between 1981 - 2017 in south-central Florida. This data package used for this analysis is comprised of three datasets all pertaining to two dominant palmetto species at Archbold Biological Station in south-central Florida created by Warren Abrahamson and Bucknell University.
Data source: Abrahamson, W.G. 2019. Survival, growth and biomass estimates of two dominant palmetto species of south-central Florida from 1981 - 2017, ongoing at 5-year intervals ver 1. Environmental Data Initiative
Palmetto saw Plant (Serenoa repens)

Show code

# wrangle the data to include only  height, canopy length, canopy width, green leaves. Change species to be names of the species and be read as characters for binary regression. 

palmetto <- read_csv(here("_posts", "2021-02-25-BinaryLogisticRegression", "palmetto.csv")) %>% 
  select(species, length, width, height, green_lvs) %>% 
  mutate(species = case_when(species == 1 ~ "Serenoa repens",
                             species == 2 ~ "Sabal etonia")) 

palmetto$species <- as.factor(palmetto$species)



Data visualization of dominant Palmetto species
Visualize the data and look for trends
Palmetto Height (cm) vs. Width (cm)


Show code

ggplot(data = palmetto, aes(x = height, y = width)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = species)) +
  facet_wrap(~species) +
  labs(x = "Height (cm)", 
       y = "Width (cm)",
       title = "Canopy height vs. width comparison for Sabal etonia and Serenoa repens",
       subtitle = "1981-2017",
       fill = "Species")




Figure 1: Figure 1. Data Vizualization of the canopy height (cm) vs. canopy width (cm) of Palmetto species, Sabal etonia and Serenoa repens. This figure includes all data collected from 1981 to 2017.



The main takeaway from this figure is that both of these species have similar relationships between the height (cm) vs. the width (cm) and are from a normally distributed sample.
Palmetto Height (cm) vs. Green Leaves (count)


Show code

ggplot(data = palmetto, aes(x = height, y = green_lvs)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color = species)) +
  facet_wrap(~species) +
  labs(x = "Height (cm)", 
    y = "Green Leaves (count)",
    title = "Canopy height vs. Green Leaves comparison for Sabal etonia and Serenoa repens",
    subtitle = "1981-2017",
    fill = "Species") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("light green", "dark green"))





Figure 2: Figure 2. Data Vizualization of the canopy height (cm) vs. number of green leaves counted of Palmetto species, Sabal etonia and Serenoa repens. This figure includes all data collected from 1981 to 2017.



Overall, the Sabal etonia has fewer green leaves in relation to height, and the Serenoa repens have a higher leaf count even at similar heights to the Sabal etonia.
Binary logistic regression


Show code

#Sabal etonia is 0 and Serenoa repens is 1
#So probability of coefficients being Sabals
palmetto_blr <- glm(species ~ length + width + height + green_lvs, 
                    data = palmetto, 
                    family = "binomial")

#palmetto_blr
#summary(palmetto_blr)



Binary logisitc regression using plant height, canopy length, canopy width and green leaves as predictor variables to understand how they relate to probability of a plant being Serenoa repens or Sabal etonia.
Table 1. Binary Logistic Regression Model for Palmetto plant species Serenoa repens and Sabal etonia using variables canopy length (cm), canopy width (cm), canopy height (cm) and leaf count.


Show code

#make a table df

palmetto_table <- palmetto_blr %>% 
  broom::tidy() %>% 
  select(estimate, std.error, p.value) %>% 
  mutate_if(is.numeric, funs(as.character(signif(.,3)))) %>% 
  slice(-1)

rownames(palmetto_table) <- c("Length (cm)",
                              "Width (cm)",
                              "Height (cm)",
                              "Green Leaves (count)")


#make a kable table

palmetto_kable <- palmetto_table %>%   
  kable(col.names = c("Estimate",
                      "Standard Error",
                      "P value")) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped",
                full_width = F,
                position = "left") %>% 
  add_header_above(c("Table 1. Binary Logistic Regression Model Results" = 4)) %>% 
  row_spec(c(1:4),
           bold = T, 
           color = "grey")

palmetto_kable




Table 1. Binary Logistic Regression Model Results





Estimate


Standard Error


P value


Length (cm)


-0.0458


0.00187


3.73e-133


Width (cm)


-0.0394

1.05e-78


Height (cm)

8.69e-37


Green Leaves (count)


1.91


0.0389

Main takeaways: All of the variables in the model had p-values that were < 0.05 with small standard errors. The reference variable in this regression was the Serenoa repens and therefore, this model showed us that with every increase in length (cm), the odds of a sample being a Serenoa repens decreased by -0.05. With every increase in width (cm), the odds of a sample being Serenoa repens decreased by -0.04. With every increase in height (cm), the odds of a sample being Serenoa repens increased 0.3 and with every additional green leaf the odds of a sample being Serenoa repens increased 1.91.
Evaluate probability of our model identifying the species correctly. Using the probability of >=50%, the species is Serenoa repens.
Table 2. Correct ID probability results for Palmetto plant species Serenoa repens and Sabal etonia.


Show code

#make a fitted df 
palmetto_fitted <- palmetto_blr %>% 
  broom::augment(type.predict = "response")

palmetto_blr_50 <- palmetto_fitted

palmetto_blr_50$species <- as.character(palmetto_blr_50$species)

#create a table of the probabilities

palmetto_prob_50 <- palmetto_fitted %>% 
  mutate(prob_50 = case_when(.fitted >= .5 ~ "Serenoa repens",
                             .fitted < .5 ~ "Sabal etonia")) %>% 
  mutate(correct = case_when(species == prob_50 ~ "Correct",
                             species != prob_50 ~ "Incorrect"))
  
palmetto_fit_table <- palmetto_prob_50 %>% 
  count(species, correct) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = correct, values_from = n) %>% 
  mutate(total = rowSums(across(where(is.numeric)))) %>% 
  mutate(percent_correct = (Correct/total*100)) %>% 
  mutate(percent_correct = round(percent_correct, digits = 2))

#make a kable table for predictions

palmetto_fit_kable <- palmetto_fit_table %>%   
  kable(col.names = c("Species", 
                      "Correct Prediction", 
                      "Incorrect Prediction", 
                      "Total Count", 
                      "% Correct")) %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "striped",
                full_width = F,
                position = "left") %>% 
  add_header_above(c("Table 2. Probability of Idenitfying Species Correctly" = 5)) %>% 
  row_spec(c(1:2),
           bold = T, 
           color = "grey")

palmetto_fit_kable




Table 2. Probability of Idenitfying Species Correctly



Species

Main takeaways: This table shows the number and percent of how accurate our binary logistic model is at predicting the correct species based on our selected variables. Our model was 92.62% accurate for predicting Sabal etonia and 90.77% correct at predicting for Serenoa repens. Overall, the model had similar correct vs. incorrect predictions for both species of palmetto plants and our model was 90%+ accurate for predicting the correct results from a large sample size (over 12,000 observations). This type of model may be useful at predicting these species in a machine learning application based on these results.

title: Circular Barplot
description: Data Visualization of global plastic waste using the circular barplot.
contents:
Show code

library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(tidyverse)
library(hrbrthemes)
library(kableExtra)
library(viridis)





Show code

#read in and wrangle the data
plastics <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2021/2021-01-26/plastics.csv')
  #mutate(across(where(is.character), tolower))

plastics$country[plastics$country == "Taiwan_ Republic of China (ROC)"] <- "Taiwan"
plastics$country[plastics$country == "United States of America"] <- "USA"
plastics$country[plastics$country == "NIGERIA"] <- "Nigeria"
plastics$country[plastics$country == "ECUADOR"] <- "Ecuador"

#tuesdata <- tidytuesdayR::tt_load('2021-01-26')
#plastics <- tuesdata$plastics

#alt df for circular barplot of countries total plastic consumption 
plastics_all <- plastics %>% 
  select(country, grand_total) %>%
  drop_na() %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarize(grand_total = sum(grand_total)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(grand_total)) %>% 
  slice(-4) %>% 
  head(15) %>% 
  mutate(country = factor(country, country))


#alt df with only grand_total plastics from top 15 countries or 4 selected parent companies in line 38
#plastics_top10 <- plastics %>% 
  #select(year, parent_company, grand_total) %>% 
  #filter(parent_company %in% c("the coca-cola company", "pepsico", "nestlé", "unilever")) %>%
  #drop_na() %>% 
  #group_by(parent_company) %>% 
  #summarize(grand_total = sum(grand_total)) %>% #or summarize(grand_total = n())
  #slice_max(grand_total, n = 15)





Show code

####make circular barplot
#_________________#

# Set a number of 'empty bar'
empty_bar=1

# Add lines to the initial plastics df
to_add = matrix(NA, empty_bar, ncol(plastics_all))
colnames(to_add) = colnames(plastics_all)
plastics_all = rbind(plastics_all, to_add)
plastics_all$id = seq(1, nrow(plastics_all))

# Get the name and the y position of each label
label_plastics = plastics_all
number_of_bar = nrow(label_plastics)
angle= 90 - 360 * (label_plastics$id-0.5) /number_of_bar # I substract 0.5 because the letter must have the angle of the center of the bars. Not extreme right(1) or extreme left (0)
label_plastics$hjust<-ifelse( angle < -90, 1, 0)
label_plastics$angle<-ifelse(angle < -90, angle + 180, angle)
label_plastics$country <- gsub("United States", "US", label_plastics$country)
label_plastics$country <- paste(label_plastics$country, " (", label_plastics$grand_total,")", sep="")

#________________#


#### Make the plot
plastics_barplot <- 
  ggplot(data = plastics_all, aes(x = as.factor(country), y = grand_total)) + # Note that id is a factor. If x is numeric, there is some space between the first bar
  geom_col(aes(fill = country), show.legend = FALSE) +
  ylim(-11900,245000) +   # Limits of the plot = very important. The negative value controls the size of the inner circle, the positive one is useful to add size over each bar
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    plot.margin = unit(rep(0,6), "cm") # This remove unnecessary margin around plot
  ) +
    coord_polar(start = 75) + # This makes the coordinate polar instead of cartesian.
  geom_text(data=label_plastics, 
            aes(x = id, y = grand_total+200, label = country), 
            color = "black", 
            fontface = "bold",
            alpha = 0.6, 
            size = 2.5, 
            angle = label_plastics$angle, 
            hjust = label_plastics$hjust,
            inherit.aes = FALSE)
 
plastics_barplot

title: Principle Components Analysis (PCA) of global environmental variables
description: Principal components analysis of nutrient contents in three types of diets.
contents:
Show code

#attach libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)
library(palmerpenguins)

#for PCA
library(ggfortify)

#for ggplot customization
library(readxl)
library(gghighlight)
library(lubridate)
library(plotly)

#to make compond figures
library(patchwork)



World Environmental Variables PCA Bioplot
Here, we’ll be assessing country-level social and economic statistics in relation to twenty-seven global environmental variables. The data includes variables such as mean temperature, mean precipitation and elevation. We’ll be using a PCA bioplot to assess the correlation between these variables across countries on a global scale. This data could serve as a way to use environmental statistics to predict social and economic data. For example, are populations happier in sunnier or cloudier places? And are there differences in country’s economies where there are higher elevations vs. lower elevations?
Data Source: Venter, Zander and Google Earth Engine
Content: This data is all acquired through Google Earth Engine where publicly available remote sensing datasets are collected. Most of the data is derived by calculating the mean for each country at a reduction scale of ~10km.


Show code

#All of your organized and well-annotated code (with warnings/messages suppressed) you wrote to wrangle data then run PCA, and to create a professional looking PCA biplot that appears (with a caption) in your knitted HTML

#read in the data and basic wrangle
world_env_var <- read_csv("world_env_vars.csv")

#pca 
world_pca <- world_env_var %>% 
  select(elevation, cropland_cover:cloudiness, -ends_with("Month"), -temp_diurnal_range, -ends_with("Quart"), slope) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  scale() %>% 
  prcomp()

# Variance explained by each PC
screeplot(world_pca, type = "lines")

world_complete <- world_env_var %>% 
  drop_na(elevation, cropland_cover:cloudiness, -ends_with("Month"), -temp_diurnal_range, -ends_with("Quart"), slope)

Show code

autoplot(world_pca, 
         data = world_complete, 
         loadings = TRUE, 
         loadings.label = TRUE,
         loading.colour = "black", 
         loadings.label.colour = "red",
         loadings.label.vjust = 2.0
         ) +
  labs(title = "PCA Biplot of World Environmental Variables") +
  theme_bw()




Figure 1: Figure 1. This PCA bioplot shows 66 percent variance of the 27 global environmental variables by country. The length of the red arrows approximates the variance of the variables, whereas the angels between them approximate their correlations.




Summary:
Strongly positively correlated variables include: tree canopy cover and cloudiness and tree cover and mean annual rainfall. In addition, tempurature seasonality and annual temperature range are also positively correlated.
Strongly neagtively correlated variables include: slope or cloudiness and rain seasonality as well as isothermality and temperature seasonality.
Not strongly correlated variables include: slope and annual temperature range, and cloudiness and mean annual temperature.
Wind, elevation, cropland cover and slope all have smaller variance than annual mean temperature, rain seasonality and cloudiness.
